{"title_page": "Zwitterion", "text_new": "A '''zwitterion''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t|s|v|\u026a|t|\u0259|\u02cc|r|a\u026a|\u0259|n}} {{respell|TSVIT|\u0259|rye|\u0259n}}; {{ety|de|Zwitter ''{{IPA-de|\u02c8tsv\u026at\u0250|}}''<nowiki />|[[hermaphrodite]]}}) is a [[molecule]] that contains an equal number of positively-charged [[functional group]](s) and negatively-charged functional group(s).<ref Name=Skoog>{{cite book |last1=Skoog |first1=Douglas, A. |last2=West |first2=Donald M. |last3=Holler |first3=F. James |last4=Crouch |first4=Stanley R. |title=Fundamentals of Analytical Chemistry |date=2004 |publisher=Thomson/Brooks/Cole |isbn=0-03-035523-0 |pages=231,385, 419,460 |edition=8th}}</ref> Zwitterions may also be called '''inner salts'''. With [[amino acid]]s, for example, in solution an [[equilibrium chemistry|chemical equilibrium]] will be established between the \"parent\" molecule and the zwitterion.\n\n[[Betaine]]s are zwitterions that cannot isomerize to an all-neutral form, such as when the positive charge is located on a [[quaternary ammonium]] group. Similarly, a molecule containing a [[phosphonium]] group and a carboxylate group cannot isomerize.\n\n==Amino acids==\n[[File:Amino Acid Zwitterion Structural Formulae V.1.svg|thumb|280px|An [[amino acid]] contains both acidic (carboxylic acid fragment) and basic (amine fragment) centres. The isomer on the right is a zwitterion.]]\n\nThe zwitterion is formed in two stages. In stage 1, a proton is transferred from the carboxyl group to a water molecule. \n:<math>H_2N(R)CO_2H + H_2O  \\leftrightharpoons H_2N(R)CO_2^- + H_3O^+</math>\nIn stage 2 a proton is transferred from the [[hydronium]] ion to the amine group\n:<math>H_2N(R)CO_2^- + H_3O^+ \\leftrightharpoons H_3N^+(R)CO_2^- + H_2O</math>\nThe reverse reactions occur in the reverse order. Overall, the reaction is an [[isomerization]] reaction\n:<math>H_2N(R)CO_2H \\leftrightharpoons H_3N^+(R)CO_2^-</math>\nThe ratio of the concentrations of the two species in solution will be independent of [[pH]] as it is equal to the value of the equilibrium constant for the isomerization reaction. \n\n:<math>K=\\frac{[H_3N^+(R)CO_2^-]}{[H_2N(R)CO_2H]}</math>\n\n[X] signifies the concentration of the chemical species X at equilibrium. The value of ''K'' cannot be determined experimentally. It is generally assumed that K>1, that is, that the zwitterion is the predominant amino acid isomer in solution. One explanation based on theoretical analysis is that the neutral form is less stable itself but becomes stabilized by [[hydrogen bonding]] with water molecules.<ref>{{cite journal |title= On the Number of Water Molecules Necessary To Stabilize the Glycine Zwitterion |first1= Jan H. |last1= Jensen |first2= Mark S. |last2= Gordon |journal= J. Am. Chem. Soc. |year= 1995 |volume= 117 |issue= 31 |pages= 8159-8170 |doi= 10.1021/ja00136a013 }}</ref> Analysis of [[neutron diffraction]] data for [[glycine]]  showed that it was in the zwitterionic form in the solid state.<ref>{{cite journal|last=J\u00f6nsson|first=P.-G.|author2=Kvick, \u00c5. |year=1972|journal=Acta Crystallographica Section B |title=Precision neutron diffraction structure determination of protein and nucleic acid components. III. The crystal and molecular structure of the amino acid \u03b1-glycine|volume=28|pages=1827\u20131833|doi=10.1107/S0567740872005096|issue=6|url=http://journals.iucr.org/b/issues/1972/06/00/a09113/a09113.pdf}}</ref> Theoretical calculations have been used to show that zwitterions may also be present in the gas phase for some cases different than the simple carboxylic acid-to-amine transfer.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Price|first=William D.|author2=Jockusch, Rebecca A. |author3=Williams, Evan R. |year=1997|title=Is Arginine a Zwitterion in the Gas Phase?|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society |volume=119 |issue=49 |pages=11988\u201311989 |doi=10.1021/ja9711627 |pmid=16479267 |pmc=1364450 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Proteinogenic amino acid| pK<sub>a</sub> values]] for deprotonation of the common amino acids span the approximate range 2.15 \u00b1 0.2. This is also consistent with the zwitterion being the predominant isomer that is present in an aqueous solution. For comparison, the carboxylic acid [[propionic acid]], RCO<sub>2</sub>H (R=CH<sub>3</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>), has pK value of 4.88.\n\n==Other compounds==\n<gallery mode=packed>\nFile:Zwitterion Structural Formulae V.1.svg|thumb|290px|right|[[Sulfamic acid]] isomers, with the zwitterion (right)\nFile:EDTA-xtal-2D-skeletal.png|thumb|right|Structure of H<sub>4</sub>EDTA </gallery>\n[[Sulfamic acid]] crystallizes in the zwitterion form.<ref name=\"Sass\">{{ cite journal | author = R. L. Sass |date=April 1960 | title = A neutron diffraction study on the crystal structure of sulfamic acid | journal = Acta Crystallogr. | volume = 13 | issue = 4 | pages = 320\u2013324 | doi = 10.1107/S0365110X60000789 }}</ref>\n\nIn the solid state, [[Aminopolycarboxylic acid|H<sub>4</sub>EDTA ]] is a zwitterion with two protons having been transferred from carboxylic acid groups to the nitrogen atoms.<ref>{{cite journal |first= Par Michel |last= Cotrait |title= La structure cristalline de l'acide \u00e9thyl\u00e8nediamine t\u00e9traac\u00e9tique, EDTA |year= 1972 |journal= Acta Crystallographica Section B |volume= 28 |pages= 781\u2013785 |doi= 10.1107/S056774087200319X }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Skoog\"/><sup>(p.460)</sup><ref>{{cite book |last1=Skoog |first1=Douglas A. |last2=West |first2=Donald M. |last3=Holler |first3=F. James |last4=Crouch |first4=Stanley R. |title=Fundamentals of Analytical Chemistry |date=2013 |publisher=Cengage |isbn=9781285607191 |pages=415\u2013416 |edition=9th}}</ref>\n\n==Betaines and similar compounds==\nA [[betaine]] is a permanent zwitterion, unlike amino acids and others that can isomerize to a fully neutral form. [[Trimethylglycine]] was the first such compound known, and was itself called simply ''betaine'' before other compounds of this class were discovered. It contains a quaternary ammonium cation and a carboxylate anion. [[Phosphatidylcholine]]s are a class of naturally-occuring betaines containing a quaternary ammonium cation and a phosphate anion found in many biological membranes.<ref>Nelson, D. L.; Cox, M. M. ''Lehninger, Principles of Biochemistry'' 3rd Ed. Worth Publishing: New York, 2000. {{ISBN|1-57259-153-6}}</ref> [[Psilocybin]] is a zwitterion in which the negatively-charged site is also a [[phosphate]] group.\n\n<gallery mode=packed>\nFile:Betaine Formula V.1.svg| [[Trimethylglycine]]\nFile:1-Oleoyl-2-almitoyl-phosphatidylcholine Structural Formulae V.1.png|thumb|Example of a [[phosphatidylcholine]]\nFile:Psilocybn.svg|[[Psilocybin]]\nFile:Cocamidopropyl betaine2.png| Lauramidopropyl betaine, the major component of [[cocamidopropyl betaine]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Azomethine ylide]]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:German words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Zwitterions| ]]\n", "text_old": "A '''zwitterion''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t|s|v|\u026a|t|\u0259|\u02cc|r|a\u026a|\u0259|n}} {{respell|TSVIT|\u0259|rye|\u0259n}}; {{ety|de|Zwitter ''{{IPA-de|\u02c8tsv\u026at\u0250|}}''<nowiki />|[[hermaphrodite]]}}) is a [[molecule]] that contains an equal number of positively-charged [[functional group]](s) and negatively-charged functional group(s).<ref Name=Skoog>{{cite book |last1=Skoog |first1=Douglas, A. |last2=West |first2=Donald M. |last3=Holler |first3=F. James |last4=Crouch |first4=Stanley R. |title=Fundamentals of Analytical Chemistry |date=2004 |publisher=Thomson/Brooks/Cole |isbn=0-03-035523-0 |pages=231,385, 419,460 |edition=8th}}</ref> Zwitterions may also be called '''inner salts'''. With [[amino acid]]s, for example, in solution an [[equilibrium chemistry|chemical equilibrium]] will be established between the \"parent\" molecule and the zwitterion.\n\n[[Betaine]]s are zwitterions that cannot isomerize to an all-neutral form, such as when the positive charge is located on a [[quaternary ammonium]] group. Similarly, a molecule containing a [[phosphonium]] group and a carboxylate group cannot isomerize.\n\n==Amino acids==\n[[File:Amino Acid Zwitterion Structural Formulae V.1.svg|thumb|280px|An [[amino acid]] contains both acidic (carboxylic acid fragment) and basic (amine fragment) centres. The isomer on the right is a zwitterion.]]\n\nThe zwitterion is formed in two stages. In stage 1, a proton is transferred from the carboxyl group to a water molecule. \n:<math>H_2N(R)CO_2H + H_2O  \\leftrightharpoons H_2N(R)CO_2^- + H_3O^+</math>\nIn stage 2 a proton is transferred from the [[hydronium]] ion to the amine group\n:<math>H_2N(R)CO_2^- + H_3O^+ \\leftrightharpoons H_3N^+(R)CO_2^- + H_2O</math>\nThe reverse reactions aoccur in the reverse order. Overall, the reaction is an [[isomerization]] reaction\n:<math>H_2N(R)CO_2H \\leftrightharpoons H_3N^+(R)CO_2^-</math>\nThe ratio of the concentrations of the two species in solution will be independent of [[pH]] as it is equal to the value of the equilibrium constant for the isomerization reaction. \n\n:<math>K=\\frac{[H_3N^+(R)CO_2^-]}{[H_2N(R)CO_2H]}</math>\n\n[X] signifies the concentration of the chemical species X at equilibrium. The value of ''K'' cannot be determined experimentally. It is generally assumed that K>1, that is, that the zwitterion is the predominant amino acid isomer in solution. One explanation based on theoretical analysis is that the neutral form is less stable itself but becomes stabilized by [[hydrogen bonding]] with water molecules.<ref>{{cite journal |title= On the Number of Water Molecules Necessary To Stabilize the Glycine Zwitterion |first1= Jan H. |last1= Jensen |first2= Mark S. |last2= Gordon |journal= J. Am. Chem. Soc. |year= 1995 |volume= 117 |issue= 31 |pages= 8159-8170 |doi= 10.1021/ja00136a013 }}</ref> Analysis of [[neutron diffraction]] data for [[glycine]]  showed that it was in the zwitterionic form in the solid state.<ref>{{cite journal|last=J\u00f6nsson|first=P.-G.|author2=Kvick, \u00c5. |year=1972|journal=Acta Crystallographica Section B |title=Precision neutron diffraction structure determination of protein and nucleic acid components. III. The crystal and molecular structure of the amino acid \u03b1-glycine|volume=28|pages=1827\u20131833|doi=10.1107/S0567740872005096|issue=6|url=http://journals.iucr.org/b/issues/1972/06/00/a09113/a09113.pdf}}</ref> Theoretical calculations have been used to show that zwitterions may also be present in the gas phase for some cases different than the simple carboxylic acid-to-amine transfer.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Price|first=William D.|author2=Jockusch, Rebecca A. |author3=Williams, Evan R. |year=1997|title=Is Arginine a Zwitterion in the Gas Phase?|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society |volume=119 |issue=49 |pages=11988\u201311989 |doi=10.1021/ja9711627 |pmid=16479267 |pmc=1364450 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Proteinogenic amino acid| pK<sub>a</sub> values]] for deprotonation of the common amino acids span the approximate range 2.15 \u00b1 0.2. This is also consistent with the zwitterion being the predominant isomer that is present in an aqueous solution. For comparison, the carboxylic acid [[propionic acid]], RCO<sub>2</sub>H (R=CH<sub>3</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>), has pK value of 4.88.\n\n==Other compounds==\n<gallery mode=packed>\nFile:Zwitterion Structural Formulae V.1.svg|thumb|290px|right|[[Sulfamic acid]] isomers, with the zwitterion (right)\nFile:EDTA-xtal-2D-skeletal.png|thumb|right|Structure of H<sub>4</sub>EDTA </gallery>\n[[Sulfamic acid]] crystallizes in the zwitterion form.<ref name=\"Sass\">{{ cite journal | author = R. L. Sass |date=April 1960 | title = A neutron diffraction study on the crystal structure of sulfamic acid | journal = Acta Crystallogr. | volume = 13 | issue = 4 | pages = 320\u2013324 | doi = 10.1107/S0365110X60000789 }}</ref>\n\nIn the solid state, [[Aminopolycarboxylic acid|H<sub>4</sub>EDTA ]] is a zwitterion with two protons having been transferred from carboxylic acid groups to the nitrogen atoms.<ref>{{cite journal |first= Par Michel |last= Cotrait |title= La structure cristalline de l'acide \u00e9thyl\u00e8nediamine t\u00e9traac\u00e9tique, EDTA |year= 1972 |journal= Acta Crystallographica Section B |volume= 28 |pages= 781\u2013785 |doi= 10.1107/S056774087200319X }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Skoog\"/><sup>(p.460)</sup><ref>{{cite book |last1=Skoog |first1=Douglas A. |last2=West |first2=Donald M. |last3=Holler |first3=F. James |last4=Crouch |first4=Stanley R. |title=Fundamentals of Analytical Chemistry |date=2013 |publisher=Cengage |isbn=9781285607191 |pages=415\u2013416 |edition=9th}}</ref>\n\n==Betaines and similar compounds==\nA [[betaine]] is a permanent zwitterion, unlike amino acids and others that can isomerize to a fully neutral form. [[Trimethylglycine]] was the first such compound known, and was itself called simply ''betaine'' before other compounds of this class were discovered. It contains a quaternary ammonium cation and a carboxylate anion. [[Phosphatidylcholine]]s are a class of naturally-occuring betaines containing a quaternary ammonium cation and a phosphate anion found in many biological membranes.<ref>Nelson, D. L.; Cox, M. M. ''Lehninger, Principles of Biochemistry'' 3rd Ed. Worth Publishing: New York, 2000. {{ISBN|1-57259-153-6}}</ref> [[Psilocybin]] is a zwitterion in which the negatively-charged site is also a [[phosphate]] group.\n\n<gallery mode=packed>\nFile:Betaine Formula V.1.svg| [[Trimethylglycine]]\nFile:1-Oleoyl-2-almitoyl-phosphatidylcholine Structural Formulae V.1.png|thumb|Example of a [[phosphatidylcholine]]\nFile:Psilocybn.svg|[[Psilocybin]]\nFile:Cocamidopropyl betaine2.png| Lauramidopropyl betaine, the major component of [[cocamidopropyl betaine]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Azomethine ylide]]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:German words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Zwitterions| ]]\n", "name_user": "Petergans", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAmino acids:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zwitterion"}
{"title_page": "Liu", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{undue weight|date=March 2020}}\n{{See also|Li\u01d4|L\u00fc (surname)|Yu (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox surname\n| name            = Liu\n| image           = SurnameLiu.svg\n| image_size      = \n| caption         = Li\u00fa surname in [[traditional Chinese characters]]p\n| pronunciation   = Li\u00fa <small>(Pinyin)</small><br/>L\u00e2u <small>([[Pe\u030dh-\u014de-j\u012b]])</small>\n| language        = Chinese, Vietnamese, Korean, Japanese \n| languageorigin  = [[Old Chinese]]\n| origin          = \n| derivation      = Surname of the [[Han dynasty]]'s ruling family\n| meaning         = \n| variant         = Li\u00fa <small>(Mandarin)</small><br/>Lau, Lao <small>(Cantonese, Hokkien, [[Teochew dialect|Teochew]])</small><br/>Lieu <small>(Shanghainese)</small><br/>L\u01b0u <small>(Vietnamese)</small><br/>Yoo, Ryu <small>(Korean)</small>\n| cognate         = \n| derivative      = \n| seealso         = [[Yoo or Ryu (Korean name)]]\n| family          = \n}}\n'''\u5289''' / '''\u5218''' (Liu, Lao, Lau, Ryu, Yoo, Leo, Lew, Lieu, Liou) is a [[Chinese surname]]. The '''Liu''' ({{IPAc-en|lj|u\u02d0}})<ref>{{cite web|title=Liu Shaoqi|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/liu-shao-qi|website=Collins English Dictionary|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> as [[Transcription (linguistics)|transcribed]] in English can represent several different surnames written in different [[Chinese characters]]:\n*[[wiktionary:\u5289|\u5289]]<small> ([[traditional characters|traditional]])</small> / [[wiktionary:\u5218|\u5218]]<small> ([[simplified characters|simplified]])</small>, [[pinyin]]: Li\u00fa in [[Mandarin Chinese]], Lau: [[Cantonese]]. A surname, as it was the family name of [[Han dynasty]] emperors.\n*[[wiktionary:\u67f3|\u67f3]] pinyin: [[Li\u01d4]] in Mandarin Chinese, Lau: Cantonese\n*[[wiktionary:\u7559|\u7559]] pinyin: Li\u00fa in Mandarin Chinese, Lau: Cantonese\n*[[wiktionary:\u516d|\u516d]] pinyin: Li\u00f9 in Mandarin Chinese, Luk: Cantonese\n*[[wiktionary:\u5ed6|\u5ed6]] pinyin: Liu6 in Cantonese, Li\u00e0o: Mandarin Chinese\n*[[wiktionary:\u4fa3|\u4fb6]] pinyin: L\u01da in Mandarin Chinese, Leoi5: Cantonese used in \u201c\u60c5\u4fa3\u201d\n\nIn [[Guangdong Romanization|Cantonese transliteration]], \u5218/\u5289 (Li\u00fa) is '''[[Lau (surname)|Lau]]''', '''Lao''' is also a transliteration of \u5218/\u5289 in [[Southern Min]] and [[Taiwanese Hokkien]], while '''Liu''' is a different surname, [[wiktionary:\u5ed6|\u5ed6]], [[pinyin]]: [[Liao (surname)|Li\u00e0o]].\n\nIn [[Shanghainese]], \u5218/\u5289 is romanized as '''Lieu''' and rarely '''Lieh'''; \u67f3 is similarly romanized; whereas \u5ed6 is transliterated as '''Lioh'''\n\nIn [[Teochew dialect|Teochew]], \u5218/\u5289 is usually romanized as '''Lau''' or '''Lao'''; \u67f3 is written as '''Lew'''; and \u5ed6 is romanized as '''Leow''' or '''Liau'''.\n\nIn [[Hakka Chinese|Hakka]],  \u5218/\u5289 is most commonly transliterated as '''Liew''' while \u5ed6 is written as '''Liau''' or '''Liaw'''. The other variants of the romanised surname '''Liu''', i.e. \u67f3, \u7559 and \u516d, are uncommon among speakers of Hakka.\n\nIn [[Gan Chinese|Gan]], \u5218/\u5289 is most commonly transliterated as '''Liew''' or '''Lieu''', \u5ed6 is written as '''Lieo''' or '''Liau'''.\n\nIn [[Bagansiapiapi|Hokkien]], \u5218/\u5289 is most commonly pronounced as Lau\n\nThe Indonesian-Chinese descent Latinise it according to Dutch pronunciation as '''Lauw'''.\n\nIn [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]], the name can either take the form '''Li\u1ec5u''' (in northern regions), or '''L\u01b0u''' (in central or southern regions), or '''L\u1ee5c'''. A few having Vietnamese-Chinese descent use the family name '''Lao'''.\n\n==Distribution==\nIn 2019 \u5218 was again the fourth most common surname in Mainland China.<ref>http://www.bjnews.com.cn/news/2020/01/20/676822.html</ref> Additionally, it was the most common surname in [[Jiangxi]] province.\n\n==Origin of Liu==\n\n===\u5289 or \u5218 (Liu, Lao, Lau, Leo, Lew, Lio, Luu, Ryu, Yu, Yoo)===\n\n*from the [[Qi (surname)#Q.C3.AD .28.E7.A5.81.29 surname|Q\u00ed (\u7941)]] clan of [[Emperor Yao]]\n*from [[King Wen of Zhou]]\n*from Liu Bang, who founded the [[Han dynasty]] as [[Emperor Gaozu of Han]]\n*from [[Xiang Bo]] of post [[Chu (state)|Chu]], who was granted the imperial family name of Liu.\n*from [[Liu Yuan (Han Zhao)|Liu Yuan]] of [[Former Zhao]]\n*from the [[Chinese compound surname]] Dugu (\u7368\u5b64) of the [[Northern Wei]]\n*from [[Liu Zhiyuan]] of [[Later Han (Five Dynasties)|Later Han]]\n\n===\u7559 (Liu, Lau, Lauv)===\n*from [[Emperor Yao]]\n*from the state of [[Zheng (state)|Zheng]] during the [[Zhou dynasty]]\n*from Liu (\u5289) family of the [[Liu Song dynasty]]\n*from the [[Miao people]]\n*from [[list of ethnic groups in China and Taiwan|ethnic groups in China and Taiwan]]\n\n===\u67f3 (Liu, Lew, Liew)===\n{{main|Li\u01d4}}\n*from the state of [[Lu (state)|Lu]] of the Zhou dynasty\n*from post-Chu state\n*from the Miao people\n*from ethnic groups in China and Taiwan\n\n===\u5ed6 (Liao, Liu, Leow, Lia)===\n{{See also|Liao (surname)}}\n*from the Zhou dynasty\n*from [[Zhurong]]\n*from the Miao people\n*from ethnic groups in China and Taiwan\n\n==Prominent people with the family name \u5218 / \u5289 ==\nCommonly transcribed Li\u00fa, Lao or Lau.\n\n===Historical figures===\n* Liu Bang, Founder of the Han dynasty as [[Emperor Gaozu of Han]]\n* [[Emperor Hui of Han|Liu Ying]] Second Emperor of the Western Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Wen of Han|Liu Heng]] Fifth Emperor of the Western Han dynasty rulers of the golden age rule Wen and Jing\n* [[Emperor Jing of Han|Liu Qi]] Sixth Emperor of the Western Han dynasty rulers of the golden age rule Wen and Jing\n* [[Emperor Wu of Han|Liu Che]] (157 BC &ndash; 87 BC) Seventh Emperor of the Western Han dynasty known for expanding the Han Dynasty to its fullest extent and for a long reign of 54 years\n* [[Liu An]] Prince and advisor to his nephew, Emperor Wu of Han. Best known for editing the (139 BC) Huainanzi compendium of Daoist, Confucianist, and Legalist teachings.\n* [[Liu Xiang (scholar)|Liu Xiang]] government official, scholar, and author of who lived during the Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Zhao of Han|Liu Fuling]] Emperor of the Western Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Xuan of Han|Liu Xun]] Emperor of the Western Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Yuan of Han|Liu Shi]] Emperor of the Western Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Cheng of Han|Liu Ao]] Emperor of the Western Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Ai of Han|Liu Xin]] Emperor of the Western Han Dynasty known to be a homosexual Emperor\n* [[Emperor Ping of Han|Liu Kan]] Emperor of the Western Han Dynasty\n* [[Liu Xin (scholar)|Liu Xin]] astronomer, historian, and editor during the Western Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Guangwu of Han|Liu Xiu]] Restorer of the Han dynasty and founder of Eastern Han \n* [[Emperor Ming of Han|Liu Zhuang]] Second Emperor of the Eastern Han Dynasty Rulers of the Golden age rule Ming and Zhang \n* [[Emperor Zhang of Han|Liu Da]] Third Emperor of the Eastern Han Dynasty Rulers of the Golden age rule Ming and Zhang \n* [[Emperor He of Han|Liu Zhao]] Fourth Emperor of the Eastern Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor An of Han|Liu Hu]] Sixth Emperor of the Eastern Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Shun of Han|Liu Bao]] Seventh Emperor of the Eastern Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Huan of Han|Liu Zhi]] Tenth Emperor of the Western Han\n* [[Emperor Ling of Han|Liu Hong]] (156 &ndash; 189) 11th Emperor of the Han dynasty\n* [[Emperor Xian of Han|Liu Xie]] (181 &ndash; 234)  Last emperor of the Han dynasty\n* [[Liu Bei]] (161 &ndash; 223) Warlord in the late Han Dynasty and founding emperor of Shu Han\n* [[Liu Zhang (warlord)|Liu Zhang]] Warlord in the late Han Dynasty\n* [[Liu Zan]] General of Eastern Wu\n* [[Liu Shan]] (207 &ndash; 271) Second emperor of Shu Han\n* [[Liu Ye (Three Kingdoms)|Liu Ye]] (163 &ndash; 232) Official and politician of Cao Wei\n* [[Liu Ba]] (186 &ndash; 222) Official and politician of Shu Han\n* [[Liu Biao]] (142 &ndash; 208) Warlord in the late Han dynasty\n* [[Liu Yuan (Han Zhao)|Liu Yuan]] founder of the Later Han\n* Liu Yu, founder of the Liu Song as [[Emperor Wu of Liu Song]]\n* Liu Yilong, [[Emperor Wen of Liu Song]]\n* [[Liu Ji (Tang chancellor)|Liu Ji]] Chancellor of the Tang Dynasty\n* [[Liu Wenjing]] Official and Chancellor of the Tang Dynasty\n* [[Liu Yan (emperor)|Liu Yan]] Founding emperor of Southern Han\n* [[Liu Zhiyuan]] Founding emperor of Later Han\n* [[Liu Chong]] Founding emperor of Northern Han\n*[[Yang Ye]] or Yang Jiye, formerly Known as Liu Jiye, military general of the Song Dynasty\n\n===Contemporary===\n* [[Natasha Liu Bordizzo]], Australian Chinese actress\n* [[Alan Lowe]], Canadian architect & politician, former mayor of [[Victoria, British Columbia]], Canada\n* [[Alicia Liu]], Taiwanese model\n* [[Amber Liu (singer)|Amber Liu]], Chinese-American member of [[f(x) (band)|f(x)]]\n* [[Andy Lau]], actor, singer\n* [[Andrew Lau]], filmmaker and actor\n* [[Anthony Liu]], figure skater\n* [[Liu Binyan]], dissident\n* [[Liu Bocheng]], PRC military commander\n* [[Liu Boming (astronaut)]]\n* [[Cecilia Liu]], Chinese actress\n* [[Liu Chao-shiuan]], Kuomintang politician\n* [[Liu Cheng-hung]], Magistrate of [[Miaoli County]] (2005\u20132014)\n* [[Liu Chengjun (general)]]\n* [[Liu Cheng-ying]], Magistrate of [[Matsu Islands|Lienchiang County]]\n* [[Liu Chien-sin]], Deputy [[Secretary-General to the President, Republic of China|Secretary General]] to the President of the [[Republic of China]]\n* [[Liu Chih-kung]], Deputy Secretary-General of [[National Security Council (Taiwan)|National Security Council]] of the [[Republic of China]] (2010\u20132012)\n* [[Liu Chih-yun]]\n* [[Liu Ching-chung]], Minister of [[Hakka Affairs Council]] (2014\u20132016)\n* [[Liu Chunyan]](1966), Chinese host and voice actress\n* [[Cixin Liu]] ({{zh|s=\u5218\u6148\u6b23|t=\u5289\u6148\u6b23|p=Li\u00fa C\u00edx\u012bn}}; born 1963) Chinese science fiction author\n* [[Liu Dalin]], sexologist\n* [[Dan Liu]], Canadian fashion designer\n* [[Evelyn Lau]], writer\n* [[Liu Fang]], Chinese Pipa and Guzheng player\n* [[Liu Fuzhi]], PRC politician\n* [[Lauw Giok Lan]] (\u5289\u7389\u862d) (1883\u20131953), Indonesian journalist and writer\n* [[Liu Guoliang]], table tennis player\n* [[Liu Heng (writer)|Liu Heng]], writer\n* [[Henry Lau]], Chinese-Canadian singer, member of [[Super Junior-M]]\n* [[Henry Liu]], journalist\n* [[Liu Huan]], singer\n* [[Liu Huaqing]] (1916\u20132011), PRC politician\n* [[Liu Hui]], mathematician\n* [[Liu I-chou]], Chairperson of [[Central Election Commission (Taiwan)|Central Election Commission]] of the [[Republic of China]] (2015\u20132017)\n* [[Isaac Liu]] (born 1991), New Zealand Rugby League player\n* [[Liu Jing (politician)]]\n* [[Liu Jinru]] (born 2000), Chinese artistic gymnast\n* [[John Liu]], [[New York City Comptroller]]\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Liu]], Taiwan representative to Spain\n* [[Liu Kang (artist)]]\n* [[Lau Kar-leung]], actor, choreographer and director\n* [[Ken Liu]], Chinese-American author\n* [[Liu Kuo-chuan]], former Deputy Minister of [[Veterans Affairs Commission]] of the [[Republic of China]]\n* [[Laurin Liu]] (born 1990), Canadian politician\n* [[Lucy Liu]] (born 1968), American actress\n* [[Liu Yuh-san]], Secretary-General of the [[Executive Yuan]] of the [[Republic of China]] (2005\u20132007)\n* [[Liu Yu-you]], Magistrate of [[Nantou County]] (1973\u20131981)\n* [[Natasha Low]], Singaporean singer, member of South Korean girl group, [[Skarf]]\n* [[Prudence Liew]], singer and actress\n* [[Liu Qi (politician, born 1942)|Liu Qi (Chinese politician)]], Beijing Olympics organizer\n* [[Liu Qi-Chao]], jazz musician\n* [[Rene Liu]], singer and actress\n* [[Rich Liu]], American actor <ref>{{cite web|title=Rich Liu - IMDB|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm6474117/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1|accessdate=28 October 2014}}</ref>\n* [[S\u00e1ndor Liu Shaolin]], Chinese-Hungarian short track speed skater\n* [[Liu Shaoqi]], PRC politician, former Chinese President\n* [[Liu Shifu]], Chinese revolutionary and anarchist\n* [[Liu Shilan]], a female Grandmaster (WGM) in chess\n* [[Liu Shishi]], Chinese actress\n* [[Sidney Lau]], Hong Kong linguist\n* [[Soung Chang Liew]], Chinese engineer\n* [[Liu Sola]], singer, composer, and writer\n* [[Tai-Ping Liu]] (born 1945), Taiwanese mathematician\n* [[Tats Lau]], Hong Kong actor and musician\n* [[Liu Tianhua]], composer and musician\n* [[Lau Wan Kit]], Hong Kong comic artist\n* [[Liu Wei (artist)]]\n* [[Liu Wen (model)|Liu Wen]], fashion model\n* [[Liu Wenhui]], warlord and PRC politician\n* [[Liu Wenjing]], one of the advisors of Tang Gaozu\n* [[Will Liu]], Taiwanese singer\n* [[Liu Xiang (hurdler)|Liu Xiang]], Olympic winner and World Record holder\n* [[Liu Xiang (warlord)]]\n* [[Liu Xiaobo]], PRC dissident and Nobel Peace Prize laureate\n* [[Liu Xiaoqing]], actress\n* [[Liu Yalou]], general\n* [[Liu Yang (astronaut)]], astronaut, first female Chinese taikonaut\n* [[Liu Yang (violinist)|Yang Liu]], classical violinist\n* [[Liu Ye (actor)]], Chinese actor\n* [[Liu Yifei]], singer/actress\n* [[Liu Yunpeng]], Chinese high jumper\n* [[Liu Yunshan]], A leader in the Communist Party of China\n* [[Liu Zhijun]], PRC politician\n* [[Liu Zhixuan]], Chinese basketball player\n* [[Nuon Chea]] (born Lau Kim Korn, 1926-) Prime Minister of Democratic Kampuchea and convicted war criminal\n* [[:pt:Christian Liu de Almeida|Christian Liu de Almeida]], (born 1997), Brazilian musician\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Liu (\u67f3)]]\n* [[Lau (surname)|Lau]]\n*{{lookfrom|Liu}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://english.people.com.cn/200507/14/eng20050714_196124.html Chinese surname history: Liu]\n{{100 Most Common Family Names in Mainland China}}\n\n{{surname}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Multiple Chinese surnames]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{undue weight|date=March 2020}}\n{{See also|Li\u01d4|L\u00fc (surname)|Yu (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox surname\n| name            = Liu\n| image           = SurnameLiu.svg\n| image_size      = \n| caption         = Li\u00fa surname in [[traditional Chinese characters]]p\n| pronunciation   = Li\u00fa <small>(Pinyin)</small><br/>L\u00e2u <small>([[Pe\u030dh-\u014de-j\u012b]])</small>\n| language        = Chinese, Vietnamese, Korean, Japanese \n| languageorigin  = [[Old Chinese]]\n| origin          = \n| derivation      = Surname of the [[Han dynasty]]'s ruling family\n| meaning         = \n| variant         = Li\u00fa <small>(Mandarin)</small><br/>Lau, Lao <small>(Cantonese, Hokkien, [[Teochew dialect|Teochew]])</small><br/>Lieu <small>(Shanghainese)</small><br/>Lieu <small>([[Gan Chinese|Gan]])</small><br/>L\u01b0u <small>(Vietnamese)</small><br/>Yoo, Ryu <small>(Korean)</small>\n| cognate         = \n| derivative      = \n| seealso         = [[Yoo or Ryu (Korean name)]]\n| family          = \n}}\n'''\u5289''' / '''\u5218''' (Liu, Lao, Lau, Ryu, Yoo, Leo, Lew, Lieu, Liou) is a [[Chinese surname]]. The '''Liu''' ({{IPAc-en|lj|u\u02d0}})<ref>{{cite web|title=Liu Shaoqi|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/liu-shao-qi|website=Collins English Dictionary|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> as [[Transcription (linguistics)|transcribed]] in English can represent several different surnames written in different [[Chinese characters]]:\n*[[wiktionary:\u5289|\u5289]]<small> ([[traditional characters|traditional]])</small> / [[wiktionary:\u5218|\u5218]]<small> ([[simplified characters|simplified]])</small>, [[pinyin]]: Li\u00fa in [[Mandarin Chinese]], Lau: [[Cantonese]]. A surname, as it was the family name of [[Han dynasty]] emperors.\n*[[wiktionary:\u67f3|\u67f3]] pinyin: [[Li\u01d4]] in Mandarin Chinese, Lau: Cantonese\n*[[wiktionary:\u7559|\u7559]] pinyin: Li\u00fa in Mandarin Chinese, Lau: Cantonese\n*[[wiktionary:\u516d|\u516d]] pinyin: Li\u00f9 in Mandarin Chinese, Luk: Cantonese\n*[[wiktionary:\u5ed6|\u5ed6]] pinyin: Liu6 in Cantonese, Li\u00e0o: Mandarin Chinese\n*[[wiktionary:\u4fa3|\u4fb6]] pinyin: L\u01da in Mandarin Chinese, Leoi5: Cantonese used in \u201c\u60c5\u4fa3\u201d\n\nIn [[Guangdong Romanization|Cantonese transliteration]], \u5218/\u5289 (Li\u00fa) is '''[[Lau (surname)|Lau]]''', '''Lao''' is also a transliteration of \u5218/\u5289 in [[Southern Min]] and [[Taiwanese Hokkien]], while '''Liu''' is a different surname, [[wiktionary:\u5ed6|\u5ed6]], [[pinyin]]: [[Liao (surname)|Li\u00e0o]].\n\nIn [[Shanghainese]], \u5218/\u5289 is romanized as '''Lieu''' and rarely '''Lieh'''; \u67f3 is similarly romanized; whereas \u5ed6 is transliterated as '''Lioh'''\n\nIn [[Teochew dialect|Teochew]], \u5218/\u5289 is usually romanized as '''Lau''' or '''Lao'''; \u67f3 is written as '''Lew'''; and \u5ed6 is romanized as '''Leow''' or '''Liau'''.\n\nIn [[Hakka Chinese|Hakka]],  \u5218/\u5289 is most commonly transliterated as '''Liew''' while \u5ed6 is written as '''Liau''' or '''Liaw'''. The other variants of the romanised surname '''Liu''', i.e. \u67f3, \u7559 and \u516d, are uncommon among speakers of Hakka.\n\nIn [[Gan Chinese|Gan]], \u5218/\u5289 is most commonly transliterated as '''Liew''' or '''Lieu''', \u5ed6 is written as '''Lieo''' or '''Liau'''.\n\nIn [[Bagansiapiapi|Hokkien]], \u5218/\u5289 is most commonly pronounced as Lau\n\nThe Indonesian-Chinese descent Latinise it according to Dutch pronunciation as '''Lauw'''.\n\nIn [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]], the name can either take the form '''Li\u1ec5u''' (in northern regions), or '''L\u01b0u''' (in central or southern regions), or '''L\u1ee5c'''. A few having Vietnamese-Chinese descent use the family name '''Lao'''.\n\n==Distribution==\nIn 2019 \u5218 was again the fourth most common surname in Mainland China.<ref>http://www.bjnews.com.cn/news/2020/01/20/676822.html</ref> Additionally, it was the most common surname in [[Jiangxi]] province.\n\n==Origin of Liu==\n\n===\u5289 or \u5218 (Liu, Lao, Lau, Leo, Lew, Lio, Luu, Ryu, Yu, Yoo)===\n\n*from the [[Qi (surname)#Q.C3.AD .28.E7.A5.81.29 surname|Q\u00ed (\u7941)]] clan of [[Emperor Yao]]\n*from [[King Wen of Zhou]]\n*from Liu Bang, who founded the [[Han dynasty]] as [[Emperor Gaozu of Han]]\n*from [[Xiang Bo]] of post [[Chu (state)|Chu]], who was granted the imperial family name of Liu.\n*from [[Liu Yuan (Han Zhao)|Liu Yuan]] of [[Former Zhao]]\n*from the [[Chinese compound surname]] Dugu (\u7368\u5b64) of the [[Northern Wei]]\n*from [[Liu Zhiyuan]] of [[Later Han (Five Dynasties)|Later Han]]\n\n===\u7559 (Liu, Lau, Lauv)===\n*from [[Emperor Yao]]\n*from the state of [[Zheng (state)|Zheng]] during the [[Zhou dynasty]]\n*from Liu (\u5289) family of the [[Liu Song dynasty]]\n*from the [[Miao people]]\n*from [[list of ethnic groups in China and Taiwan|ethnic groups in China and Taiwan]]\n\n===\u67f3 (Liu, Lew, Liew)===\n{{main|Li\u01d4}}\n*from the state of [[Lu (state)|Lu]] of the Zhou dynasty\n*from post-Chu state\n*from the Miao people\n*from ethnic groups in China and Taiwan\n\n===\u5ed6 (Liao, Liu, Leow, Lia)===\n{{See also|Liao (surname)}}\n*from the Zhou dynasty\n*from [[Zhurong]]\n*from the Miao people\n*from ethnic groups in China and Taiwan\n\n==Prominent people with the family name \u5218 / \u5289 ==\nCommonly transcribed Li\u00fa, Lao or Lau.\n\n===Historical figures===\n* Liu Bang, Founder of the Han dynasty as [[Emperor Gaozu of Han]]\n* [[Emperor Hui of Han|Liu Ying]] Second Emperor of the Western Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Wen of Han|Liu Heng]] Fifth Emperor of the Western Han dynasty rulers of the golden age rule Wen and Jing\n* [[Emperor Jing of Han|Liu Qi]] Sixth Emperor of the Western Han dynasty rulers of the golden age rule Wen and Jing\n* [[Emperor Wu of Han|Liu Che]] (157 BC &ndash; 87 BC) Seventh Emperor of the Western Han dynasty known for expanding the Han Dynasty to its fullest extent and for a long reign of 54 years\n* [[Liu An]] Prince and advisor to his nephew, Emperor Wu of Han. Best known for editing the (139 BC) Huainanzi compendium of Daoist, Confucianist, and Legalist teachings.\n* [[Liu Xiang (scholar)|Liu Xiang]] government official, scholar, and author of who lived during the Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Zhao of Han|Liu Fuling]] Emperor of the Western Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Xuan of Han|Liu Xun]] Emperor of the Western Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Yuan of Han|Liu Shi]] Emperor of the Western Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Cheng of Han|Liu Ao]] Emperor of the Western Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Ai of Han|Liu Xin]] Emperor of the Western Han Dynasty known to be a homosexual Emperor\n* [[Emperor Ping of Han|Liu Kan]] Emperor of the Western Han Dynasty\n* [[Liu Xin (scholar)|Liu Xin]] astronomer, historian, and editor during the Western Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Guangwu of Han|Liu Xiu]] Restorer of the Han dynasty and founder of Eastern Han \n* [[Emperor Ming of Han|Liu Zhuang]] Second Emperor of the Eastern Han Dynasty Rulers of the Golden age rule Ming and Zhang \n* [[Emperor Zhang of Han|Liu Da]] Third Emperor of the Eastern Han Dynasty Rulers of the Golden age rule Ming and Zhang \n* [[Emperor He of Han|Liu Zhao]] Fourth Emperor of the Eastern Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor An of Han|Liu Hu]] Sixth Emperor of the Eastern Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Shun of Han|Liu Bao]] Seventh Emperor of the Eastern Han Dynasty\n* [[Emperor Huan of Han|Liu Zhi]] Tenth Emperor of the Western Han\n* [[Emperor Ling of Han|Liu Hong]] (156 &ndash; 189) 11th Emperor of the Han dynasty\n* [[Emperor Xian of Han|Liu Xie]] (181 &ndash; 234)  Last emperor of the Han dynasty\n* [[Liu Bei]] (161 &ndash; 223) Warlord in the late Han Dynasty and founding emperor of Shu Han\n* [[Liu Zhang (warlord)|Liu Zhang]] Warlord in the late Han Dynasty\n* [[Liu Zan]] General of Eastern Wu\n* [[Liu Shan]] (207 &ndash; 271) Second emperor of Shu Han\n* [[Liu Ye (Three Kingdoms)|Liu Ye]] (163 &ndash; 232) Official and politician of Cao Wei\n* [[Liu Ba]] (186 &ndash; 222) Official and politician of Shu Han\n* [[Liu Biao]] (142 &ndash; 208) Warlord in the late Han dynasty\n* [[Liu Yuan (Han Zhao)|Liu Yuan]] founder of the Later Han\n* Liu Yu, founder of the Liu Song as [[Emperor Wu of Liu Song]]\n* Liu Yilong, [[Emperor Wen of Liu Song]]\n* [[Liu Ji (Tang chancellor)|Liu Ji]] Chancellor of the Tang Dynasty\n* [[Liu Wenjing]] Official and Chancellor of the Tang Dynasty\n* [[Liu Yan (emperor)|Liu Yan]] Founding emperor of Southern Han\n* [[Liu Zhiyuan]] Founding emperor of Later Han\n* [[Liu Chong]] Founding emperor of Northern Han\n*[[Yang Ye]] or Yang Jiye, formerly Known as Liu Jiye, military general of the Song Dynasty\n\n===Contemporary===\n* [[Natasha Liu Bordizzo]], Australian Chinese actress\n* [[Alan Lowe]], Canadian architect & politician, former mayor of [[Victoria, British Columbia]], Canada\n* [[Alicia Liu]], Taiwanese model\n* [[Amber Liu (singer)|Amber Liu]], Chinese-American member of [[f(x) (band)|f(x)]]\n* [[Andy Lau]], actor, singer\n* [[Andrew Lau]], filmmaker and actor\n* [[Anthony Liu]], figure skater\n* [[Liu Binyan]], dissident\n* [[Liu Bocheng]], PRC military commander\n* [[Liu Boming (astronaut)]]\n* [[Cecilia Liu]], Chinese actress\n* [[Liu Chao-shiuan]], Kuomintang politician\n* [[Liu Cheng-hung]], Magistrate of [[Miaoli County]] (2005\u20132014)\n* [[Liu Chengjun (general)]]\n* [[Liu Cheng-ying]], Magistrate of [[Matsu Islands|Lienchiang County]]\n* [[Liu Chien-sin]], Deputy [[Secretary-General to the President, Republic of China|Secretary General]] to the President of the [[Republic of China]]\n* [[Liu Chih-kung]], Deputy Secretary-General of [[National Security Council (Taiwan)|National Security Council]] of the [[Republic of China]] (2010\u20132012)\n* [[Liu Chih-yun]]\n* [[Liu Ching-chung]], Minister of [[Hakka Affairs Council]] (2014\u20132016)\n* [[Liu Chunyan]](1966), Chinese host and voice actress\n* [[Cixin Liu]] ({{zh|s=\u5218\u6148\u6b23|t=\u5289\u6148\u6b23|p=Li\u00fa C\u00edx\u012bn}}; born 1963