ellowship|url=http://students.anu.edu.au/scholarships/gr/off/int/paterson-fellowship.php|accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref> and the Robert Hill Memorial Prize for excellence in scientific research, communication and outreach.<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert Hill Memorial Prize|url=http://students.anu.edu.au/graduation/prizes/cpms/robert-hill-memorial-prize.php|accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref>\n\n==Research==\nAbram's research expertise spans Antarctic and tropical climate systems. She uses [[Porites]] corals, [[Speleothem]] samples from caves and [[Ice core]] samples to reconstruct [[Climate change (general concept)|climate changes in the past]] to provide a crucial long-term perspective on [[Climate change|recent and projected future climate changes]]. Abram's publication record includes first-author papers across the scientific journals of [[Science (journal)|''Science'']], [[Nature (journal)|''Nature'']], ''[[Nature Geoscience]]'', and ''[[Nature Climate Change]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nerilie Abram|url=https://scholar.google.com.au/citations?user=yWwLiyYAAAAJ&hl=en |website=Google Scholar|accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2004 and 2011 Abram was an ice core scientist with the [[British Antarctic Survey]]. Here, she was part of the team that drilled the [[James Ross Island]] ice core in 2008. Dr Abram's discoveries from this project included that the [[Antarctic Peninsula]] is warming very rapidly,<ref>{{Cite web|title=15000 years of Antarctic Peninsula climate history|url = http://www.sciencepoles.org/interview/15000-years-of-antarctic-peninsula-climate-history|accessdate = 18 August 2014|website =Science Poles}}</ref> resulting in a 10-fold increase summer ice melt in that area of Antarctica.<ref>{{Cite web|title=What is happening to Antarctica's ice?|url = http://theconversation.com/explainer-what-is-happening-to-antarcticas-ice-13684|accessdate = 18 August 2014|website = the Conversation}}</ref>\n\nAbram was part of the chemical analysis team of the NEEM ice core project in Northern [[Greenland]] in 2010 which sought to retrieve ice from the [[Eemian]] inter-glacial period to discover what Earth would be like under the effects of global warming.<ref name=\"NEEM\">{{cite web |url=http://neem.dk/about_neem/ |title=About NEEM |accessdate=14 August 2014 |publisher=[[University of Copenhagen]]}}</ref>  In the summer of 2013/14 Abram was also a member of the international team that drilled the Aurora Basin ice core in East Antarctica.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.antarctica.gov.au/science/climate-processes-and-change/antarctic-palaeoclimate/aurora-basin/people-in-the-field/nerilie-abram-driller-and-ice-core-chemist|title = Australian Antarctic Division \"People in the field\" Profile.|date =28 October 2013 |accessdate = 14 August 2014|website =Australian Government Department of the Environment |publisher =Australian Government |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 Abram demonstrated that the southward shift in westerly winds caused by greenhouse gas emissions has moved these winds to their most southward position in at least the last 1,000 years causing a marked reduction in rainfall in southern Australia.<ref>{{cite news|title=Research shows Antarctica may be the reason for SA dry climate|url=http://www.abc.net.au/am/content/2014/s4002380.htm|accessdate=15 August 2014|publisher=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|date=14 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Science communication==\n\nAbram is a dedicated science communicator, and her work has been covered by international print, online, radio and television media outlets. She has also been interviewed for documentaries including the BBC ''[[Men of Rock]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Studying Ice Cores, The Big Freeze|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p011smzs|accessdate=18 August 2014|publisher=BBC2}}</ref> series hosted by [[Iain Stewart (geologist)|Iain Stewart]], and for the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] exhibition of [[Robert Falcon Scott|Robert Scott]]\u2019s final expedition.<ref>{{cite web|title=Studying Ice Cores in Antarctica|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VjTsj-fi-p0|accessdate=18 August 2014|publisher=Natural History Museum}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Abram wrote an invited essay on Antarctic ice melt and sea level rise for ''The Curious Country'',<ref>{{cite web|title=The Curious Country|url=http://press.anu.edu.au/titles/the-curious-country/|accessdate=18 August 2014|publisher=[[ANU Press]]}}</ref> a book about the importance of Australian science published for the [[Office of the Chief Scientist (Australia)]]. This work was later selected for republication in the anthology of Best Australian Science Writing 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Best Australian Science Writing 2014|url=https://www.newsouthbooks.com.au/books/best-australian-science-writing-2014/|accessdate=30 June 2016|publisher=New South}}</ref>\n\nAbram is a mother of three children and has a strong interest in encouraging other women in scientific careers. Her work as an Antarctic scientist and mother was the subject of a profile piece for \u201cI don\u2019t know how she does it\u201d in the Times Magazine, London.<ref>{{cite web|title=I don\u2019t know how she does it|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/life/article2943199.ece|website=Times Magazine, London|accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n\nIn 2011, Abram returned to Australia after being awarded a QEII fellowship through the [[Australian Research Council]].<ref>{{cite web|title=ANU Discovery Projects commencing in 2011|url=http://www.arc.gov.au/pdf/DP11/ARC_Discovery_Projects_2011_Round_1-Application_Detail_Summary_The_Australian_National_University.pdf|website=Australian Research Council|accessdate=2014-08-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140212031121/http://www.arc.gov.au/pdf/DP11/ARC_Discovery_Projects_2011_Round_1-Application_Detail_Summary_The_Australian_National_University.pdf|archivedate=2014-02-12}}</ref> In 2014 Abram received a second ARC Discovery Grant to continue her groundbreaking work studying the effects of tropical and Antarctic climate change on Australia's rainfall patterns.<ref>{{cite web|title= Discovery Projects commencing in 2014|url= http://www.arc.gov.au/pdf/DP14/DP14_Listing_by_State_and_Org.pdf|website= Australian Research Council|accessdate= 2014-08-14|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140308002742/http://www.arc.gov.au/pdf/DP14/DP14_Listing_by_State_and_Org.pdf|archivedate= 2014-03-08}}</ref> Abram was the 2015 recipient of the [[Dorothy Hill Medal|Dorothy Hill award]] from the Australian Academy of Science which recognises excellence in Earth Sciences research by a woman under the age of 40.<ref>{{cite web|title= Dorothy Hill Award|url= https://www.science.org.au/opportunities-scientists/recognition/honorific-awards/early-career-awards/dorothy-hill-award|website=Australian Academy of Science|accessdate=2016-06-30}}</ref>\n\nAbram is Co-Editor-in-Chief for the open-access journal ''Climate of the Past'' since 2010, a journal that is associated with the [[European Geosciences Union]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Editorial Board|url= http://www.climate-of-the-past.net/editorial_board.html|website=Climate of the Past|accessdate=2014-08-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://rses.anu.edu.au/people/nerilie-abram ANU Profile of Dr Nerilie Abram]\n*[https://scholar.google.com.au/citations?user=yWwLiyYAAAAJ&hl=en Dr Nerilie Abram] on [[Google Scholar]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abram, Nerilie}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian women scientists]]\n[[Category:Australian National University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:Australian National University alumni]]\n[[Category:Climate change environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Antarctic scientists]]\n[[Category:Women Antarctic scientists]]\n", "name_user": "Kj cheetham", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u2